It doesn't give numbers and I can't find numbers anywhere on this, but I think it was mentioned in the documentary - let's assume it is true.<br>
<br>
Since a large portion of firearm homicides are at the hands of persons close to the victim, I doubt that learning people to use guns would help.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, criminals will always have the initiative. If you make the population more able and more willing to use lethal force to defend themselves, you will only create more ruthless criminals, who are quicker to use lethal force themselves.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I also honestly believe(redneckish as it is) that if everyone owned a gun(w/ proper training), violent crimes would drop<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.vpc.org/studies/wher2gen.htm">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> : <br>
<br>
- Members of handgun-owning families were twice as likely to die in a suicide or homicide as members of the same age, sex, and neighborhood who had no history of handgun purchase. <br>
- These increased risks persisted for more than five years after the purchase.<br>
<br>
The notion that the ability to arm yourself will increase your safety is not supported by the facts.<br>
<br>
------------------------<br>
<br>
Okay, onto the original question.<br>
<br>
I think there's multiple reasons.<br>
<br>
- Availability. The fact that this is apparently not as large a problem elsewhere as it is in the US does not discount this as a possible cause for the high homicide rates.<br>
- Higher crime rates overall. Why exactly this is, I have no idea, but maybe US citizens are quicker to disobey the law than elsewhere.<br>
- Ghetto's. Ghetto's are an heritage of slavery and apartheid. Violence is very common there.<br>
<br>
Also, there might be differences in registration in the US and Canada, a difference in unregistered gunownership and a difference in ease of obtaining a gun legally or illegally, that make the two countries less comparable. <p>---------------<br>
