<br>
You are incorrect sir, both grammatically and factually. Ghettos are created through the process of urbanization. Here's what happens, and I can give my own neighborhood as a perfect example. I live on a beautiful tree lined street in New Haven, CT which is lined for miles with beautiful 3 story victorians that were once the pride of the Westville area. In the 1920s, a phenomenon arose known as &quot;blockbusting&quot;. My neighborhood and many others in many metro areas fell prey to this. What would happen is this:<br>
<br>
Crooked real estate guy buys beautiful victorian A.<br>
CREG (Crooked Real Estate Guy) then pays to have the house cut into 3, 4, sometimes as many as 6 separate apartments. <br>
CREG then rents out these apartments to immigrant and other low income families. <br>
When this happens to hundreds of houses in a neighborhood you see a number of things happening. <br>
A) the population of a neighborhood at least triples.<br>
B) the property value of a neighborhood drops<br>
C) the average income of a neighborhood drops<br>
D) over time the general quality of the neighborhood declines, career criminals begin setting up shop in these neighborhoods, leading to drug blocks, gang blocks, etc. Its easier to operate in a neighborhood where the cops don't come because they don't really care about the poor people. WHY the local government allows these areas to degenerate like this is an entirely different and much stinkier can of corruption, er, worms.<br>
<br>
THIS is where ghettos come from. Slavery and apartheid have nothing to do with &quot;ghettos&quot;. Not in a direct sense anyway. I suppose you could make the connection between poor families of former slaves having no other opportunities for places to live I suppose, but I think that's a stretch. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=550521"><br>
Svarien Doesntlikeyou<br>
